FT  24 AUG 93 / Commodities and Agriculture: Natal sugar growers struggle
against drought
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   DURBAN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SUGAR GROWERS in Natal are struggling to save what they can of the
drought-stricken 1993-1994 crop, which is expected to yield only 1.2m
tonnes, down 300,000 tonnes from last year and 900,000 tonnes below the
normal level, according to industry officials, reports Reuter from Durban.
'There was some rain in parts of Zululand but it is not going to do anything
to this crop. It might save the cane roots from dying,' South African Sugar
Cane Growers' Association executive director Mr Rex Hudson said.
He added that the Natal south coast and midlands were the worst affected
production areas. Extensive replanting would have to be done as a result of
the drought, he said.
