<HEADLINE>
FT  24 AUG 93 / WPP cautious on fragile upturn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WPP GROUP, the marketing services company, remains cautious about an upturn
in its markets in spite of reporting pre-tax profits of Pounds 24.1m, up
from Pounds 1.8m, in the half year to June 30. The result was helped by the
absence of last year's Pounds 13.5m restructuring charge.
Mr Martin Sorrell, chief executive, said: 'The economic recovery, such as it
is, remains delicate and unsettled especially in the US and the UK. On the
basis of client experience to date, it is possible that a recovery will be
delayed for some time.'
The group is paying an interim dividend of 0.35p, as it forecast at the time
of its rights issue in March: the first payout since 1990. The shares rose
3p to 93p.
Reorganisation and rationalisation costs of Pounds 3.9m covered severance
pay. Operating profit before this cost rose to Pounds 46.5m (from Pounds
35.1m). Billings increased to Pounds 2.9bn (from Pounds 2.5bn) and group
revenues rose by 16.4 per cent to Pounds 699.8m, although more than 10 per
cent of that rise was due to the weaker pound.
Revenues in media advertising increased by 7.4 per cent in the first half. J
Walter Thompson and Ogilvy &amp; Mather generated net new business billings of
more than Pounds 156m (Dollars 235m) and Pounds 117m (Dollars 176m)
respectively.
However, while US advertising is showing signs of recovery, the group voiced
its concern about the extent to which President Clinton's tax proposals
could affect US companies, which in turn might cut back on their
advertising.
Public relation companies continued to lose money. Hill &amp; Knowlton and
Ogilvy Adams &amp; Rinehart reported combined losses of Pounds 4.8m, up from
Pounds 400,000.
Net debt fell to Pounds 372m (from Pounds 476m) resulting in a lower
interest charge of Pounds 15.6m (from Pounds 20.5m).
The average net debt figure reflects three months of proceeds of its Pounds
85m rights issue.
The group hopes to reduce borrowings further with the sale of Scali McCabe
Sloves, the US agency. That sale is expected to fetch between Dollars 40m
(Pounds 26.8m) and Dollars 60m.
In the long-term, WPP is considering the flotation of its market research
activities in south-east Asia and the sale of one or two smaller companies.
Earnings per share of 2.5p compare with a loss of 7.6p.
Lex, Page 14
</TEXT>
