<HEADLINE>
FT  24 AUG 93 / Exchange acts to lift share liquidity
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE LONDON Stock Exchange said that, from yesterday, trading prices for
smaller stocks will be more widely disseminated in an effort to increase
liquidity in less liquid issues.
The trading prices are for about 160 shares with only one registered
marketmaker or with no marketmaker and for which bargains must be transacted
through matching offers posted on the Stock Exchange Alternative Trading
Service (Seats).
Marketmakers have increasingly withdrawn their services from smaller
capitalised companies with shares traded on the exchange, greatly
diminishing liquidity for investors.
Since last November the exchange has been operating its Seats system with
price transparency - the last price at which a share was traded - available
only through its Topic screen.
From yesterday the exchange is making bargains in less liquid stocks
available to information vendors such as Reuters and Bloomberg at no
additional charge. Those information providers already sell exchange share
price information to users who do not have the Topic screen.
The service should make access to price quotes available to investors
outside the UK who would not normally have access to the Topic screen.
The improved service was developed by the London Stock Exchange in
conjunction with Andersen Consulting.
</TEXT>
