<DATE>930824
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  24 AUG 93 / Curbs on secrecy 'not enough'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE CAMPAIGN for Freedom of Information yesterday attacked government plans
to reduce secrecy, saying they did not go far enough.
The pressure group said last month's white paper on open government
contained some 'positive' elements but stopped well short of delivering
freedom of information.
There was now 'a foot in the door,' it said in the August issue of its
Secrets newspaper.
It was particularly critical of the proposed code of practice which would
require Whitehall to comply with reasonable requests for information.
Too many of the code's proposals represent victories for the 'culture of
government secrecy' which Mr William Waldegrave, the public services
minister, was trying to overturn.
The code's 'overwhelming, central flaw' was its rejection of direct access
to documents. The government was promising to answer questions, not let
people see correspondence, documents or reports.
The group welcomed the proposed statutory right of access to
non-computerised personal files and health and safety information.
Mr Waldegrave said last month that public access to information would be
restricted only where there were good reasons.
Secrets. The Campaign for Freedom of Information, 88 Old Street, London EC1V
9AR.
</TEXT>
