<HEADLINE>
FT  23 AUG 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
First work in BBC Proms Live (7.30 BBC2 and Radio 3) is '(K) ein Sommernacht
straum' or '(Not) A Midsummer Night's Dream' by Schnittke, played by the
Oslo Philharmonic under conductor Mariss Jansons. They also play Richard
Strauss's outsize 'Alpine Symphony', beginning at about 8.40. In between
comes Tchaikovsky's Violin Concerto, with Japanese soloist Midori. She began
her career as an 11-year-old prodigy, recorded this concerto at 15 and now,
at 21, is making her Proms debut.
World In Action has had a neat idea: after all the accounts of British
tourists' misfortunes abroad, they have sent a reporter undercover to see
how tourists fare in Britain. The answer seems to be: ripped off by minicabs
and ticket touts (8.30 ITV).
A former ticket tout is central to the ITV drama series Frank Stubbs
Promotes (9.00). The opening series ends today with Stubbs, played by
Timothy Spall, turning himself into a literary agent.
Come Dancing ends its series with a Dutch/British contest (11.05 BBC1).
